        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Spectral setup: Baseband 1 has been configured to observe the CO(3-2) line in Band 7 at a sky frequency of 337.73 GHz. The bandwidth of 1.875 GHz (equivalent to 1668 km/s) and channel width of 3.904 MHz (after averaging over 8 channels, for a resolution of ~ 3.5 km/s) is sufficient for observing the expected line widths (FWHM) of 20 km/s up to 500 km/s seen in the circumnuclear regions of nearby Seyfert Galaxies. Maiolino et al. (1997) observed a CO(1-0) FWHM line widths of 205 km/s for Mrk 590 with the 12m NRAO single dish telescope. In Band 7, we can make full use of ALMA's correlator flexibility by configuring Baseband 2 to observe the HCO+(4-3) line at a sky frequency of 347.66 GHz, with approximately the same bandwidth and spectral resolution. We expect the CO(3-2) and HCO+(4-3) line to have FWHM of order ~ 200 km/s as well. We use the remaining two base bands for dust continuum observations centered at sky frequencies of 335.64 GHz and 349.61 GHz, for minimal overlap between the base bands and maximum aggregate bandwidth.

We take advantage of the unprecedented angular resolutions offered by ALMA Cycle 2 at these frequencies to observe at 0.23" resolution, equivalent to 119 pc at the source, allowing us to resolve regions at these scales close to the nucleus to detect warm and dense molecular gas, while maintaining sufficient brightness sensitivity. The maximum recoverable scale in the most extended configuration is ~ 2.7" (equivalent to 1.4 kpc at the source) per spectral channel. We expect this to be sufficient; in NGC 4151 for example, the largest angular scale structure observed in the circumnuclear region is ~ 1.3 kpc across. We therefore do not require ACA observations or more compact configurations on the main array. The central third of the field of view where the sensitivity is optimum is about 6" (equivalent to 3.2 kpc), which is sufficient for probing the circumnuclear regions. We note that the maximum recoverable scale and field of view may be larger, since we do not require the most extended array configuration for our required resolution.

We require 0.7 mJy per beam sensitivity levels (0.14 K at 0.23" resolution), which would need 54.76 minutes integration on source (2.51 hrs total including calibration and overheads, which would at the same time give us a very good uv-coverage to image possible complex structures and high dynamic range close to the central continuum source). This allows us to trace molecular gas masses down to levels of 1.21 x 10^6 solar masses per 0.23" beam, assuming a H2 to CO conversion factor of alpha_CO = 0.8 pc^-2(K kms^-1)^-1, as has been observed in the circumnuclear regions of nearby galaxies (Sandstrom et al., 2013), and that the line luminosity of C(3-2) is 70% (using the value in between that of a QSO and that of the Milky Way given in Carilli &amp; Walter (2013)) that of the line luminosity of CO(1-0). We can thus detect mass surface densities down to ~ 85 solar masses/pc^2 at 5 sigma, assuming uniform distribution over the synthesized beam, which is lower than that observed for giant molecular clouds (typically 100 solar masses/pc (Solomon et al. 1987)). In the circumnuclear regions of NGC4151 for example, gas masses of ~ 150 solar masses/pc^2 have been detected in gas lanes in the central 2.6 kpc (Dumas et al., 2010). As we have good reasons to believe that the surface density of the nuclear gas may be low in the central sub-kpc regions of Mrk 590, this sensitivity will be sufficient to probe much lower level mass surface densities, or at the very least place very strong constraints on the amount of molecular gas left in the central kpc regions.

At the aggregated bandwidth of ~ 7 GHz, we obtain a continuum flux sensitivity of 0.03 mJy per beam, equivalent to 6 mK at 0.23" resolution. We can therefore detect dust continuum down to ~ 30 mK levels at 5 sigma. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
